---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
    title="@scope and LSCSS"
    description="How CSS @scope fits into Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparisons</p>

        <h1>
            CSS @scope and LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Scope strengthens many existing LSCSS ideas rather than replacing
            them.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Original LSCSS approach
        </h2>

<pre><code>.product-card > .title {
    margin: 0;
}

.product-card > .price {
    color: var(--colour-accent);
}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Scoped LSCSS approach
        </h2>

<pre><code>@scope (.product-card) {
    .title {
        margin: 0;
    }

    .price {
        color: var(--colour-accent);
    }
}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What remains important
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>explicit cascade layers</li>
            <li>semantic component naming</li>
            <li>modifier classes</li>
            <li>state classes</li>
            <li>layered architecture</li>
            <li>migration boundaries</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Likely future direction
        </h2>

        <p>
            As browser support improves, LSCSS will likely shift toward scoped
            component partials with reduced selector verbosity.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
